      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat: add skill usage telemetry — real-time exec-to-skill tracking",
        "body": "## Problem\n\nThere is currently no way to distinguish between skills that are **actually used** (CLI executed) vs merely discovered (SKILL.md scanned at startup). Users with 30+ installed skills have no visibility into which ones bring real value.\n\nFixes #85263\n\n## Solution\n\nInstrument the exec-tool execution path to track skill invocations in real time.\n\n### Changes\n\n| File | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `src/agents/skills/skill-bins.ts` (new) | Builds skill→CLI binary mapping from loaded skills |\n| `src/agents/skills/usage-tracker.ts` (new) | Telemetry module — atomic writes, in-memory cache, 1000-invocation cap per skill |\n| `src/agents/skills/workspace.ts` (modified) | Exports `getSkillBinsMap()`, populated during skill loading |\n| `src/agents/bash-tools.exec.ts` (modified) | Tracks skill invocations on exec success/failure |\n| `src/cli/skills-cli.ts` (modified) | Adds `openclaw skills usage` subcommand with `--since`, `--agent`, `--json` options |\n\n### How it works\n\n1. Skills load → build bin→skill map from `requires.bins` / `requires.anyBins`\n2. Each exec → extract first word of command, match against map\n3. Match found → record to `~/.openclaw/agents/{agentId}/skill-usage.json`\n4. View → `openclaw skills usage [--since 7d] [--agent xxx] [--json]`\n\n### Known limitations\n\n1. Only covers skills that declare `requires.bins` (CLI-based skills)\n2. First-match wins when multiple skills share a binary\n3. Backgrounded/yielded exec is not tracked\n4. Does not correlate prior `read SKILL.md` with subsequent `exec` calls\n\n### Verification\n\n- `npx tsc --noEmit` passes with zero errors",
